@Node "MS Log LogUser" "GMS_mailer.guide/MailerSettings/Log/LogUser"
@Prev "MS Log LogTransfer"
@Toc  "MS Log"

Name:      LogUser=<level>

Level=<Silent|Terse|Discreet|Verbose|Talkative|Excessive|Annoying|Monologue>

   Set the value for <LogUser> keyword.

   This log are written by the arexx GMS_mailer_Write_Log function.


Example:   LogUser=Monologue

@EndNode

@Node "MS Modem" "GMS_mailer.guide/MailerSettings/Modem"
@Next "MS Pts"
@Prev "MS Log"
@Toc  "CFG MailerSettings"

   @{b}Modem options@{ub}


   How to configure your modem string...

 @{" Answer             " Link "MS Modem Answer"}
 @{" ArqString          " Link "MS Modem ArqString"}
 @{" ModemAnswer        " Link "MS Modem ModemAnswer"}
 @{" ModemData          " Link "MS Modem ModemData"}
 @{" ModemDialPre       " Link "MS Modem ModemDialPre"}
 @{" ModemDialPost      " Link "MS Modem ModemDialPost"}
 @{" ModemHangUp        " Link "MS Modem ModemHangUp"}
 @{" ModemInit          " Link "MS Modem ModemInit"}
 @{" SniffArq           " Link "MS Modem SniffArq"}
 @{" StrModem           " Link "MS Modem StrModem"}
 @{" StrModemBusy       " Link "MS Modem StrModemBusy"}
 @{" StrModemConnect    " Link "MS Modem StrModemConnect"}
 @{" StrModemData       " Link "MS Modem StrModemData"}
 @{" StrModemDialing    " Link "MS Modem StrModemDialing"}
 @{" StrModemError      " Link "MS Modem StrModemError"}
 @{" StrModemNoAnswer   " Link "MS Modem StrModemNoAnswer"}
 @{" StrModemNoCarrier  " Link "MS Modem StrModemNoCarrier"}
 @{" StrModemNoDialtone " Link "MS Modem StrModemNoDialtone"}
 @{" StrModemOk         " Link "MS Modem StrModemOk"}
 @{" StrModemRing       " Link "MS Modem StrModemRing"}
 @{" StrModemRinging    " Link "MS Modem StrModemRinging"}
 @{" StrModemVoice      " Link "MS Modem StrModemVoice"}

@EndNode

@Node "MS Modem Answer" "GMS_mailer.guide/MailerSettings/Modem/Answer"
@Next "MS Modem ArqString"
@Toc  "MS Modem"

Name:      Answer=<boolean>

   Forces  GMS  mailer  to  operate in "answer mode".  Then GMS mailer will
wait  for  a  call,  answer  the  phone and try to start a session with the
remote system.


Example:   Answer=ON

@EndNode

@Node "MS Modem ArqString" "GMS_mailer.guide/MailerSettings/Modem/ArqString"
@Next "MS Modem ModemAnswer"
@Prev "MS Modem Answer"
@Toc  "MS Modem"

Name:      ArqString=<expression>

   Tells  GMS  mailer  what  string  the  modem returns when it connects to
another  modem  under  an error-control protocol.  HST modems, for example,
returns the string "ARQ" as in "CONNECT 9600/ARQ/HST/HST".

   You  must  setup  the  correct  <ArqString>  for your modem when you use
<SniffArq>.


Example:   ArqString=#?(ARQ|X.|LAPM|V32B)#?


See also:     @{"SniffArq" Link "MS Modem SniffArq"}

@EndNode

@Node "MS Modem ModemAnswer" "GMS_mailer.guide/MailerSettings/Modem/ModemAnswer"
@Next "MS Modem ModemData"
@Prev "MS Modem ArqString"
@Toc  "MS Modem"

Name:      ModemAnswer=<string>

   This  string  is  sent to the modem whenever GMS mailer detects a `RING'
and wants to answer the phone.


Example:   ModemAnswer=ATA|

@EndNode

@Node "MS Modem ModemData" "GMS_mailer.guide/MailerSettings/Modem/ModemData"
@Next "MS Modem ModemDialPre"
@Prev "MS Modem ModemAnswer"
@Toc  "MS Modem"

Name:      ModemData=<string>

   This  string  is  sent to the modem whenever GMS mailer detects a `DATA'
string.  It's useful for US Robotics modems configured in Fax Mode 1.


Example:   ModemData=ATO|

@EndNode

@Node "MS Modem ModemDialPre" "GMS_mailer.guide/MailerSettings/Modem/ModemDialPre"
@Next "MS Modem ModemDialPost"
@Prev "MS Modem ModemData"
@Toc  "MS Modem"

Name:      ModemDialPre=<string>

   This  string  is  sent  to the modem whenever GMS mailer wants to dial a
number.   After  sending  this  string,  GMS mailer will send the telephone
number to dial, followed by the <ModemDialPost> string.


Example:   ModemDialPre=ATDP


See also:     @{"ModemDialPost" Link "MS Modem ModemDialPost"}

@EndNode

@Node "MS Modem ModemDialPost" "GMS_mailer.guide/MailerSettings/Modem/ModemDialPost"
@Next "MS Modem ModemHangUp"
@Prev "MS Modem ModemDialPre"
@Toc  "MS Modem"

Name:      ModemDialPost=<string>

   This  string  is  sent to the modem after the telephone number, when GMS
Mailer wants to dial a number.


Example:   ModemDialPost=|


See also:     @{"ModemDialPre" Link "MS Modem ModemDialPre"}

@EndNode

@Node "MS Modem ModemHangUp" "GMS_mailer.guide/MailerSettings/Modem/ModemHangUp"
@Next "MS Modem ModemInit"
@Prev "MS Modem ModemDialPost"
@Toc  "MS Modem"

Name:      ModemHangUp=<string>

   This  string will be sent to the modem whenever GMS mailer wants to hang
up the line.


Example:   ModemHangUp=|^|

@EndNode

@Node "MS Modem ModemInit" "GMS_mailer.guide/MailerSettings/Modem/ModemInit"
@Next "MS Modem SniffArq"
@Prev "MS Modem ModemHangUp"
@Toc  "MS Modem"

Name:      ModemInit=<string>

   This string will be sent to the modem during the initialization phase of
GMS mailer.

- If the modem send `OK' all proceed.
- If the modem send "ERROR" GMS mailer exits.


Example:   ModemInit=~~ATZ|

@EndNode

@Node "MS Modem SniffArq" "GMS_mailer.guide/MailerSettings/Modem/SniffArq"
@Next "MS Modem StrModem"
@Prev "MS Modem ModemInit"
@Toc  "MS Modem"

Name:      SniffArq=<boolean>

   If  you  have  a  modem  that  will  detect  MNP, LAP-M, V42 and similar
error-correction  protocols,  with  this  keyword, GMS mailer will minimize
session-startup delays.


Example:   SniffArq=OFF

@EndNode

@Node "MS Modem StrModem" "GMS_mailer.guide/MailerSettings/Modem/StrModem"
@Next "MS Modem StrModemBusy"
@Prev "MS Modem SniffArq"
@Toc  "MS Modem"

Name:      StrModem=<Default|Custom>

   With  this  keyword you can decide to use internal Hayes modem string or
configure it yourself.

   In  this  way  you  can  configure  GMS mailer for others standard modem
response.


Example:   StrModem=Default

@EndNode

@Node "MS Modem StrModemBusy" "GMS_mailer.guide/MailerSettings/Modem/StrModemBusy"
@Next "MS Modem StrModemConnect"
@Prev "MS Modem StrModem"
@Toc  "MS Modem"

Name:      StrModemBusy=<string>

   This  string  will  be  matched with the string returned by the modem to
determine if the line is busy.


Example:   StrModemBusy=BUSY

@EndNode

@Node "MS Modem StrModemConnect" "GMS_mailer.guide/MailerSettings/Modem/StrModemConnect"
@Next "MS Modem StrModemData"
@Prev "MS Modem StrModemBusy"
@Toc  "MS Modem"

Name:      StrModemConnect=<string>

   This  string  will  be  matched with the string returned by the modem to
determine if there is a connection.


Example:   StrModemConnect=CONNECT

@EndNode

@Node "MS Modem StrModemData" "GMS_mailer.guide/MailerSettings/Modem/StrModemData"
@Next "MS Modem StrModemDialing"
@Prev "MS Modem StrModemConnect"
@Toc  "MS Modem"

Name:      StrModemData=<string>

   This  string  will  be  matched with the string returned by the modem to
determine if there is a data connection.


Example:   StrModemData=DATA

@EndNode

@Node "MS Modem StrModemDialing" "GMS_mailer.guide/MailerSettings/Modem/StrModemDialing"
@Next "MS Modem StrModemError"
@Prev "MS Modem StrModemData"
@Toc  "MS Modem"

Name:      StrModemDialing=<string>

   This  string  will  be  matched with the string returned by the modem to
determine if the modem dialing.


Example:   StrModemDialing=DIALING

@EndNode

@Node "MS Modem StrModemError" "GMS_mailer.guide/MailerSettings/Modem/StrModemError"
@Next "MS Modem StrModemNoAnswer"
@Prev "MS Modem StrModemDialing"
@Toc  "MS Modem"

Name:      StrModemError=<string>

   This  string  will  be  matched with the string returned by the modem to
determine if there is an error.


Example:   StrModemError=ERROR

@EndNode

@Node "MS Modem StrModemNoAnswer" "GMS_mailer.guide/MailerSettings/Modem/StrModemNoAnswer"
@Next "MS Modem StrModemNoCarrier"
@Prev "MS Modem StrModemError"
@Toc  "MS Modem"

Name:      StrModemNoAnswer=<string>

   This  string  will  be  matched with the string returned by the modem to
determine if the other end does not respond.


Example:   StrModemNoAnswer="NO ANSWER"

@EndNode

@Node "MS Modem StrModemNoCarrier" "GMS_mailer.guide/MailerSettings/Modem/StrModemNoCarrier"
@Next "MS Modem StrModemNoDialtone"
@Prev "MS Modem StrModemNoAnswer"
@Toc  "MS Modem"

Name:      StrModemNoCarrier=<string>

   This  string  will  be  matched with the string returned by the modem to
determine if the connection is lost.


Example:   StrModemNoCarrier="NO CARRIER"

@EndNode

@Node "MS Modem StrModemNoDialtone" "GMS_mailer.guide/MailerSettings/Modem/StrModemNoDialtone"
@Next "MS Modem StrModemOk"
@Prev "MS Modem StrModemNoCarrier"
@Toc  "MS Modem"

Name:      StrModemNoDialtone=<string>

   This  string  will  be  matched with the string returned by the modem to
determine if there is a no dialtone error.


Example:   StrModem="NO DIAL"

@EndNode

@Node "MS Modem StrModemOk" "GMS_mailer.guide/MailerSettings/Modem/StrModemOk"
@Next "MS Modem StrModemRing"
@Prev "MS Modem StrModemNoDialtone"
@Toc  "MS Modem"

Name:      StrModemOk=<string>

   This  string  will  be  matched with the string returned by the modem to
determine if all is ok.


Example:   StrModemOk=OK

@EndNode

@Node "MS Modem StrModemRing" "GMS_mailer.guide/MailerSettings/Modem/StrModemRing"
@Next "MS Modem StrModemRinging"
@Prev "MS Modem StrModemOk"
@Toc  "MS Modem"

Name:      StrModemRing=<string>

   This  string  will  be  matched with the string returned by the modem to
determine if the phone rings.


Example:   StrModemRing=RING

@EndNode

@Node "MS Modem StrModemRinging" "GMS_mailer.guide/MailerSettings/Modem/StrModemRinging"
@Next "MS Modem StrModemVoice"
@Prev "MS Modem StrModemRing"
@Toc  "MS Modem"

Name:      StrModemRinging=<string>

   This  string  will  be  matched with the string returned by the modem to
determine if the phone of the other side rings.


Example:   StrModemRinging=RINGING

@EndNode

@Node "MS Modem StrModemVoice" "GMS_mailer.guide/MailerSettings/Modem/StrModemVoice"
@Prev "MS Modem StrModemRinging"
@Toc  "MS Modem"

Name:      StrModemVoice=<string>

   This  string  will  be  matched with the string returned by the modem to
determine if there is a voice on the other side.


Example:   StrModemVoice=VOICE

@EndNode

@Node "MS Pts" "GMS_mailer.guide/MailerSettings/Protocols"
@Next "MS Serial"
@Prev "MS Modem"
@Toc  "CFG MailerSettings"

   @{b}Protocol options@{ub}


   How to set up all protocols supported by GMS mailer.

 @{" DietIfna       " Link "MS Pts DietIfna"}
 @{" SeaLink        " Link "MS Pts SeaLink"}
 @{" ZedZip         " Link "MS Pts ZedZip"}
 @{" ZedZap         " Link "MS Pts ZedZap"}
 @{" DirectZap      " Link "MS Pts DirectZap"}
 @{" Hydra          " Link "MS Pts Hydra"}

 @{" HydraUni       " Link "MS Pts HydraUni"}
 @{" HydraBaud      " Link "MS Pts HydraBaud"}
 @{" HydraString    " Link "MS Pts HydraString"}

@EndNode

@Node "MS Pts DietIfna" "GMS_mailer.guide/MailerSettings/Protocols/DietIfna"
@Next "MS Pts SeaLink"
@Toc  "MS Pts"

Name:      DietIfna=<boolean>

   Enable/disable DietIfna mode.  DietIfna is the XModem transfer protocol.
It  will  not  switch block sizes, but use a fixed block size of 128 bytes.
It will resume an interrupted transfer if possible.

   It works only under YooHoo handshake !


Example:   DietIfna=ON

@EndNode

@Node "MS Pts SeaLink" "GMS_mailer.guide/MailerSettings/Protocols/SeaLink"
@Next "MS Pts ZedZap"
@Prev "MS Pts DietIfna"
@Toc  "MS Pts"

Name:      SeaLink=<boolean>

   Enable/disable SeaLink mode.  SeaLink is the XModem transfer protocol.
It  will  not  switch block sizes, but use a fixed block size of 128 bytes.
It will resume an interrupted transfer if possible.

   It works only under Emsi and Emsi-II handshakes !


Example:   SeaLink=ON

@EndNode

@Node "MS Pts ZedZip" "GMS_mailer.guide/MailerSettings/Protocols/ZedZip"
@Next "MS Pts ZedZap"
@Prev "MS Pts SeaLink"
@Toc  "MS Pts"

Name:      ZedZip=<boolean>

   Enable/disable ZedZip mode.  ZedZip is the ZModem transfer protocol.  It
will  not switch block sizes, but use a fixed block size of 1024 bytes.  It
will resume an interrupted transfer if possible.


Example:   ZedZip=ON

@EndNode

@Node "MS Pts ZedZap" "GMS_mailer.guide/MailerSettings/Protocols/ZedZap"
@Next "MS Pts DirectZap"
@Prev "MS Pts ZedZip"
@Toc  "MS Pts"

Name:      ZedZap=<boolean>

   Enable/disable  ZedZap  mode.   ZedZap is a slight variant of the ZModem
transfer  protocol  -- on large files, this is one of the fastest protocols
around.   ZedZap  will  automatically switch block sizes depending on modem
speed and quality of the line.  It will also resume an interrupted transfer
if possible.


Example:   ZedZap=ON

@EndNode

@Node "MS Pts DirectZap" "GMS_mailer.guide/MailerSettings/Protocols/DirectZap"
@Next "MS Pts Hydra"
@Prev "MS Pts ZedZap"
@Toc  "MS Pts"

Name:      DirectZap=<boolean>

   Enable/disable  DirectZap  mode.   DirectZap  is a slight variant of the
ZedZap  transfer  protocol, which is a slight variant of Zmodem -- on large
files,  this  is one of the fastest protocol GMS mailer has to offer.  Like
ZedZap,  DirectZap will automatically switch block sizes depending on modem
speed and quality of the line.  It will also resume an interrupted transfer
if possible. This is the fastest unidirectional protocol.


Example:   DirectZap=ON

@EndNode

@Node "MS Pts Hydra" "GMS_mailer.guide/MailerSettings/Protocols/Hydra"
@Next "MS Pts HydraUni"
@Prev "MS Pts DirectZap"
@Toc  "MS Pts"

Name:      Hydra=<boolean>

   Enable/disable  Hydra  mode.  Hydra is a new bidirectional file transfer
protocol  --  on  large files, this is the fastest protocol that GMS mailer
has  to  offer.   Hydra  will automatically switch block sizes depending on
modem  speed and quality line.  It will also resume an interrupted transfer
if possible.


Example:   Hydra=ON

@EndNode

@Node "MS Pts HydraUni" "GMS_mailer.guide/MailerSettings/Protocols/HydraUni"
@Next "MS Pts HydraBaud"
@Prev "MS Pts Hydra"
@Toc  "MS Pts"

Name:      HydraUni=<boolean>

   Enable/disable Hydra to work in unidirectional mode. This means Hydra
connections will ONLY be unidirectional!


Example:   HydraUni=OFF

@EndNode

@Node "MS Pts HydraBaud" "GMS_mailer.guide/MailerSettings/Protocols/HydraBaud"
@Next "MS Pts HydraString"
@Prev "MS Pts HydraUni"
@Toc  "MS Pts"

Name:      HydraBaud=<baud>

   Minimal baudrate to enable Hydra file transfer protocol.


Example:   HydraBaud=2400


See also:     @{"Hydra" Link "MS Pts Hydra"}, @{"HydraString" Link "MS Pts HydraString"}

@EndNode

@Node "MS Pts HydraString" "GMS_mailer.guide/MailerSettings/Protocols/HydraString"
@Prev "MS Pts HydraBaud"
@Toc  "MS Pts"

Name:      HydraString=<expression>

   Is the string that GMS mailer search in connect response to enable Hydra
file transfer protocol.


Example:   HydraString=#?(ARQ|X.|LAP-M|V32B)#?


See also:     @{"Hydra" Link "MS Pts Hydra"}, @{"HydraBaud" Link "MS Pts HydraBaud"}

@EndNode

@Node "MS Serial" "GMS_mailer.guide/MailerSettings/Serial"
@Next "MS Specials"
@Prev "MS Pts"
@Toc  "CFG MailerSettings"

   @{b}Serial options@{ub}


   How to set up your serial port...

 @{" 7Wire         " Link "MS Serial 7Wire"}
 @{" Baud          " Link "MS Serial Baud"}
 @{" Dsr           " Link "MS Serial Dsr"}
 @{" EOFMode       " Link "MS Serial EOFMode"}
 @{" Lock          " Link "MS Serial Lock"}
 @{" MaxBaud       " Link "MS Serial MaxBaud"}
 @{" MinBaud       " Link "MS Serial MinBaud"}
 @{" SerialBufSize " Link "MS Serial SerialBufSize"}
 @{" SerialName    " Link "MS Serial SerialName"}
 @{" SerialUnit    " Link "MS Serial SerialUnit"}
 @{" SerialFlags   " Link "MS Serial SerialFlags"}
 @{" Shared        " Link "MS Serial Shared"}
 @{" SlowModem     " Link "MS Serial SlowModem"}

@EndNode

@Node "MS Serial 7Wire" "GMS_mailer.guide/MailerSettings/Serial/7Wire"
@Next "MS Serial Baud"
@Toc  "MS Serial"

Name:      7Wire=<boolean>

   Enable/disable  7-wire cabling.  This will instruct the serial device to
use  (or  not to use) the CTS and RTS signals.  If you are using high speed
modems  with  data compression, such as a US Robotics Courier HST, you must
use  <7Wire>  handshake and you must set your modem to "hardware handshake"
mode, otherwise various difficulties will arise.


Example:   7Wire=ON

@EndNode

@Node "MS Serial Baud" "GMS_mailer.guide/MailerSettings/Serial/Baud"
@Next "MS Serial Dsr"
@Prev "MS Serial 7Wire"
@Toc  "MS Serial"

Name:      Baud=<baudrate>

   This  is the baudrate to initially talk to the modem -- after a power-on
or  a reset.  This speed may change during a session, when you did not lock
the baudrate.


Example:   Baud=2400
           Baud=38400

See also:     @{"Lock" Link "MS Serial Lock"}

@EndNode

@Node "MS Serial Dsr" "GMS_mailer.guide/MailerSettings/Serial/Dsr"
@Next "MS Serial EOFMode"
@Prev "MS Serial Baud"
@Toc  "MS Serial"

Name:      Dsr=<boolean>

   After  GMS  mailer  opens  the serial.device, it will wait a short while
(depending  on  <SlowModem>) and then sample the `DSR' line.  If GMS mailer
doesn't find `DSR' activated, it will report error and abort.


Example:   Dsr=ON


See also:     @{"SlowModem" Link "MS Serial SlowModem"}

@EndNode

@Node "MS Serial EOFMode" "GMS_mailer.guide/MailerSettings/Serial/EOFMode"
@Next "MS Serial Lock"
@Prev "MS Serial Dsr"
@Toc  "MS Serial"

Name:      EOFMode=<boolean>

   With  this  keyword  you  can  minimize the cpu load during an the Hydra
session.

   Remember  that some buggied serial devices does not support this feature
and  if  you  set  ON this option with these kind of devices you can obtain
only errors !


Example:   EOFMode=ON

@EndNode

@Node "MS Serial Lock" "GMS_mailer.guide/MailerSettings/Serial/Lock"
@Next "MS Serial MaxBaud"
@Prev "MS Serial EOFMode"
@Toc  "MS Serial"

Name:      Lock=<boolean>

   Lock the baudrate.  If the baudrate is locked, and GMS mailer receives a
`CONNECT  XXXX' message from the modem, GMS mailer will @{b}not@{ub} adjust the baud
rate to XXXX, but continue to operate at the rate specified with the <Baud>
keyword.


Example:   Lock=OFF


See also:     @{"Baud" Link "MS Serial Baud"}

@EndNode

@Node "MS Serial MaxBaud" "GMS_mailer.guide/MailerSettings/Serial/MaxBaud"
@Next "MS Serial MinBaud"
@Prev "MS Serial Lock"
@Toc  "MS Serial"

Name:      MaxBaud=<boolean>

   If  turned  on, the <MinBaud> parameter will automatically be set to the
baudrate  of  the called system (found in the nodelist) or the own baudrate
(set with <Baud>) on outgoing calls, whichever is lower.


Example:   MaxBaud=NO


See also:     @{"MinBaud" Link "MS Serial MinBaud"}

@EndNode

@Node "MS Serial MinBaud" "GMS_mailer.guide/MailerSettings/Serial/MinBaud"
@Next "MS Serial SerialBufSize"
@Prev "MS Serial MaxBaud"
@Toc  "MS Serial"

Name:      MinBaud=<minbaud>

   Minimal  baudrate  to establish a connection.  Connections at baud rates
below  this  limit  will not be allowed, no matter if incoming or outgoing.
If  the  baud  rate is lower than the specified value, GMS mailer will send
the <MinBaudBanner> then will hang up immediately


Example:   MinBaud=2400


See also:     @{"ModemHangUp" Link "MS Modem ModemHangUp"}

@EndNode

@Node "MS Serial SerialBufSize" "GMS_mailer.guide/MailerSettings/Serial/SerialBufSize"
@Next "MS Serial SerialName"
@Prev "MS Serial MinBaud"
@Toc  "MS Serial"

Name:      SerialBufSize=<bytes>

   This keyword can be used to set the serial receive buffer.


Examples:  SerialBufSize=16384

@EndNode

@Node "MS Serial SerialName" "GMS_mailer.guide/MailerSettings/Serial/SerialName"
@Next "MS Serial SerialUnit"
@Prev "MS Serial SerialBufSize"
@Toc  "MS Serial"

Name:      SerialName=<string>

   If  you  happen  to have a modem connected to some other device than the
standard  Amiga  "serial.device",  you can use this parameter to set up the
correct  device name.  Usually, the default of "serial.device" will just be
about perfect.

   For Supra 2400zi modems, use the "modem0.device".  


Examples:  SerialName=serial.device
           SerialName=artser.device
           SerialName=gvpser.device

@EndNode

@Node "MS Serial SerialUnit" "GMS_mailer.guide/MailerSettings/Serial/SerialUnit"
@Next "MS Serial SerialFlags"
@Prev "MS Serial SerialName"
@Toc  "MS Serial"

Name:      SerialUnit=<unit>

   If  your  modem  is connected to some other unit number than zero change
this appropriately.


Example:   SerialUnit=0


See also:     @{"SerialName" Link "MS Serial SerialName"}

@EndNode

@Node "MS Serial SerialFlags" "GMS_mailer.guide/MailerSettings/Serial/SerialFlags"
@Next "MS Serial Shared"
@Prev "MS Serial SerialUnit"
@Toc  "MS Serial"

Name:      SerialFlags=<flags>

   If  you  use  some  other device than "serial.device", you might need to
change  this,  too.   Consult  the  documentation that came with your other
device or use the default of zero.


Example:   SerialFlags=0


See also:     @{"SerialName" Link "MS Serial SerialName"}

@EndNode

@Node "MS Serial Shared" "GMS_mailer.guide/MailerSettings/Serial/Shared"
@Next "MS Serial SlowModem"
@Prev "MS Serial SerialFlags"
@Toc  "MS Serial"

Name:      Shared=<boolean>

   Open the serial device in shared mode.  If you are running GMS mailer in
conjunction  with  a  BBS program or similar, you need to switch the serial
device  to  <Shared=ON> mode, so that both programs can have it open at the
same time.


Example:   Shared=OFF


See also:     @{"SerialName" Link "MS Serial SerialName"}, @{"SerialUnit" Link "MS Serial SerialUnit"}

@EndNode

@Node "MS Serial SlowModem" "GMS_mailer.guide/MailerSettings/Serial/SlowModem"
@Prev "MS Serial Shared"
@Toc  "MS Serial"

Name:      SlowModem=<delay>

   If define the time that GMS mailer waits between lowering and raising of
DTR when it tries to reset the modem or hang up,

   In this version the <delay> value is a multiple of 100 mS.


Example:   SlowModem=10


See also:     @{"Dsr" Link "MS Serial Dsr"}

@EndNode

@Node "MS Specials" "GMS_mailer.guide/MailerSettings/Specials"
@Next "MS System"
@Prev "MS Serial"
@Toc  "CFG MailerSettings"

   @{b}Special options@{ub}


   Very special options :-)

 @{" Allow4DBundles  " Link "MS Specials Allow4DBundles"}
 @{" AllowMultiFReqs " Link "MS Specials AllowMultiFReqs"}
 @{" AllowRefusing   " Link "MS Specials AllowRefusing"}
 @{" AlwaysHangUp    " Link "MS Specials AlwaysHangUp"}
 @{" BeepDisplay     " Link "MS Specials BeepDisplay"}
 @{" BiSendMail      " Link "MS Specials BiSendMail"}
 @{" BiSendFlo       " Link "MS Specials BiSendFlo"}
 @{" BiSendRlo       " Link "MS Specials BiSendRlo"}
 @{" DiskIORead      " Link "MS Specials DiskIORead"}
 @{" DiskIOWrite     " Link "MS Specials DiskIOWrite"}
 @{" ExitOnError     " Link "MS Specials ExitOnError"}
 @{" HoldAll         " Link "MS Specials HoldAll"}
 @{" HoldXMail       " Link "MS Specials HoldXMail"}
 @{" HoldFReqs       " Link "MS Specials HoldFReqs"}
 @{" HoldTics        " Link "MS Specials HoldTics"}
 @{" HydraPrefs      " Link "MS Specials HydraPrefs"}
 @{" Immediate       " Link "MS Specials Immediate"}
 @{" ListedOnly      " Link "MS Specials ListedOnly"}
 @{" MaxError        " Link "MS Specials MaxError"}
 @{" MaxErrorSize    " Link "MS Specials MaxErrorSize"}
 @{" NLAlwaysOpened  " Link "MS Specials NLAlwaysOpened"}
 @{" OldTruncate     " Link "MS Specials OldTruncate"}
 @{" OutFReqs        " Link "MS Specials OutFReqs"}
 @{" Pickup          " Link "MS Specials Pickup"}
 @{" PresentAkas     " Link "MS Specials PresentAkas"}
 @{" ProcessOnly4D   " Link "MS Specials ProcessOnly4D"}
 @{" RetryDosRead    " Link "MS Specials RetryDosRead"}
 @{" RetryDosWrite   " Link "MS Specials RetryDosWrite"}
 @{" SkipDupes       " Link "MS Specials SkipDupes"}
 @{" SlotsType       " Link "MS Specials SlotsType"}
 @{" TaskPri         " Link "MS Specials TaskPri"}
 @{" TrapListPatch   " Link "MS Specials TrapListPatch"}

@EndNode

@Node "MS Specials Allow4DBundles" "GMS_mailer.guide/MailerSettings/Specials/Allow4DBundles"
@Next "MS Specials AllowRefusing"
@Toc  "MS Specials"

Name:      Allow4DBundles=<boolean>

   GMS  mailer  tell the remote to send bundles as they are in his outbound
without renaming them in 2D.


Example:   AllowRefusing=OFF

@EndNode

@Node "MS Specials AllowMultiFReqs" "GMS_mailer.guide/MailerSettings/Specials/AllowMultiFReqs"
@Next "MS Specials AllowRefusing"
@Prev "MS Specials Allow4DBundles"
@Toc  "MS Specials"

Name:      AllowMultiFReqs=<boolean>

   Tell  the remote site to does not send multiple #?.REQ files in the same
session.

   This keyword works only in a Emsi-II session !


Example:   AllowMultiFReqs=ON

@EndNode

@Node "MS Specials AllowRefusing" "GMS_mailer.guide/MailerSettings/Specials/AllowRefusing"
@Next "MS Specials AlwaysHangUp"
@Prev "MS Specials AllowMultiFReqs"
@Toc  "MS Specials"

Name:      AllowRefusing=<boolean>

   When  AllowRefusing  is  enabled,  GMS  mailer  respects the other end's
wishes  in  the Emsi handshake.  When the other end states it does not want
to  receive  any  compressed  mail,  for example, GMS mailer won't send it.
With  AllowRefusing=NO,  GMS  mailer  will always send what has to be sent.
This keyword defaults to ON.


Example:   AllowRefusing=ON

@EndNode

@Node "MS Specials AlwaysHangUp" "GMS_mailer.guide/MailerSettings/Specials/AlwaysHangUp"
@Next "MS Specials BeepDisplay"
@Prev "MS Specials AllowRefusing"
@Toc  "MS Specials"

Name:      AlwaysHangUp=<boolean>

   When  AlwaysHangUp  is  enabled, GMS mailer always sends the ModemHangUp
string to the modem also when it is already hung up.


Example:   AlwaysHangUp=OFF

@EndNode

@Node "MS Specials BeepDisplay" "GMS_mailer.guide/MailerSettings/Specials/BeepDisplay"
@Next "MS Specials BiSendMail"
@Prev "MS Specials AlwaysHangUp"
@Toc  "MS Specials"

Name:      BeepDisplay=<boolean>

   GMS  mailer  will  flash  the  screen  when  the  modem send a `CONNECT'
message.


Example:   BeepDisplay=ON

@EndNode

@Node "MS Specials BiSendMail" "GMS_mailer.guide/MailerSettings/Specials/BiSendMail"
@Next "MS Specials BiSendFlo"
@Prev "MS Specials BeepDisplay"
@Toc  "MS Specials"

Name:      BiSendMail=<First|Sencond|All>

   With  Hydra,  specify  in  which bidirectional file batch GMS mailer can
send #?.(OUT|CUT|DUT|HUT) files.


Example:   BiSendMail=All

@EndNode

@Node "MS Specials BiSendFlo" "GMS_mailer.guide/MailerSettings/Specials/BiSendFlo"
@Next "MS Specials BiSendRlo"
@Prev "MS Specials BiSendMail"
@Toc  "MS Specials"

Name:      BiSendFlo=<First|Sencond|All>

   With  Hydra,  specify  in  which bidirectional file batch GMS mailer can
send #?.(FLO|CLO|DLO|HLO) files.


Example:   BiSendFlo=First

@EndNode

@Node "MS Specials BiSendRlo" "GMS_mailer.guide/MailerSettings/Specials/BiSendRlo"
@Next "MS Specials DiskIORead"
@Prev "MS Specials BiSendFlo"
@Toc  "MS Specials"

Name:      BiSendRlo=<First|Sencond|All>

   With  Hydra,  specify  in  which bidirectional file batch GMS mailer can
send #?.RLO files.


Example:   BiSendRlo=First

@EndNode

@Node "MS Specials DiskIORead" "GMS_mailer.guide/MailerSettings/Specials/DiskIORead"
@Next "MS Specials DiskIOWrite"
@Prev "MS Specials BiSendRlo"
@Toc  "MS Specials"

Name:      DiskIORead=<decimal>

   You  can  specify a fixed buffer to read the data that it has to be sent
to the remote system instead of a read for every packet.


Example:   DiskIORead=16384

@EndNode

@Node "MS Specials DiskIOWrite" "GMS_mailer.guide/MailerSettings/Specials/DiskIOWrite"
@Next "MS Specials ExitOnError"
@Prev "MS Specials DiskIORead"
@Toc  "MS Specials"

Name:      DiskIOWrite=<decimal>

   You  can specify a fixed buffer to write the data from the remote system
instead of a write for every packet.


Example:   DiskIOWrite=16384

@EndNode

@Node "MS Specials ExitOnError" "GMS_mailer.guide/MailerSettings/Specials/ExitOnError"
@Next "MS Specials HoldAll"
@Prev "MS Specials DiskIOWrite"
@Toc  "MS Specials"

Name:      ExitOnError=<boolean>

   If in an outgoing call the modem return VOICE, NO DIALTONE or ERROR, GMS
Mailer continues the redial cycle.


Example:   ExitOnError=ON

@EndNode

@Node "MS Specials HoldAll" "GMS_mailer.guide/MailerSettings/Specials/HoldAll"
@Next "MS Specials HoldXMail"
@Prev "MS Specials ExitOnError"
@Toc  "MS Specials"

Name:      HoldAll=<boolean>

   With  this  keyword you tell the remote system to do not send mail, file
attach and file requests.


Example:   HoldAll=OFF

@EndNode

@Node "MS Specials HoldXMail" "GMS_mailer.guide/MailerSettings/Specials/HoldXMail"
@Next "MS Specials HoldFReqs"
@Prev "MS Specials HoldAll"
@Toc  "MS Specials"

Name:      HoldXMail=<boolean>

   With  this  keyword  you  tell the remote system to do not send mail and
file attach.


Example:   HoldXMail=ON

@EndNode

@Node "MS Specials HoldFReqs" "GMS_mailer.guide/MailerSettings/Specials/HoldFReqs"
@Next "MS Specials HoldTics"
@Prev "MS Specials HoldXMail"
@Toc  "MS Specials"

Name:      HoldFReqs=<boolean>

   With  this  keyword  you  tell  the  remote  system  to do not send file
requests.


Example:   HoldFReqs=ON

@EndNode

@Node "MS Specials HoldTics" "GMS_mailer.guide/MailerSettings/Specials/HoldTics"
@Next "MS Specials HydraPrefs"
@Prev "MS Specials HoldFReqs"
@Toc  "MS Specials"

Name:      HoldTics=<boolean>

   With  this  keyword  you  tell  the  remote  system  to do not send file
attach, ticks and bundles.

   This keyword works only under Emsi-II handshake !!


Example:   HoldTics=OFF

@EndNode

@Node "MS Specials HydraPrefs" "GMS_mailer.guide/MailerSettings/Specials/HydraPrefs"
@Next "MS Specials Immediate"
@Prev "MS Specials HoldTics"
@Toc  "MS Specials"

Name:      HydraPrefs=<boolean>

   Indicates  that  under  the  Hydra  protocol,  batch  one  contains file
requests only, while batch 2 is reserved for all other files.

   This keyword works only under Emsi-II handshake !!


Example:   HydraPrefs=ON

@EndNode

@Node "MS Specials Immediate" "GMS_mailer.guide/MailerSettings/Specials/Immediate"
@Next "MS Specials ListedOnly"
@Prev "MS Specials HydraPrefs"
@Toc  "MS Specials"

Name:      Immediate=<boolean>

   If set to ON GMS starts a session immediately, then quit itself.


Example:   Immediate=OFF

@EndNode

@Node "MS Specials ListedOnly" "GMS_mailer.guide/MailerSettings/Specials/ListedOnly"
@Next "MS Specials MaxError"
@Prev "MS Specials Immediate"
@Toc  "MS Specials"

Name:      ListedOnly=<boolean>

   GMS  search  in  the  nodelist  if  there  is at least one of the remote
addresses  in  it.   If there isn't or if there isn't a password set for one 
of those remote addresses, it hang up the session.


Example:   ListedOnly=OFF

@EndNode

@Node "MS Specials MaxError" "GMS_mailer.guide/MailerSettings/Specials/MaxError"
@Next "MS Specials MaxErrorSize"
@Prev "MS Specials ListedOnly"
@Toc  "MS Specials"

Name:      MaxError=<decimal>

   In  an  outgoing  call, GMS mailer hang up when file transfer errors are
more than MaxError in the size intervall specified by MaxErrorSize.

   With MaxError=0 you disable this feature.


Example:   MaxError=5

@EndNode

@Node "MS Specials MaxErrorSize" "GMS_mailer.guide/MailerSettings/Specials/MaxErrorSize"
@Next "MS Specials NLAlwaysOpened"
@Prev "MS Specials MaxError"
@Toc  "MS Specials"

Name:      MaxErrorSize=<boolean>

   In  an  outgoing  call, GMS mailer hang up when file transfer errors are
more than MaxError in the size intervall specified by MaxErrorSize.

   With MaxErrorSize=0 you disable this feature.


Example:   MaxErrorSize=20000

@EndNode

@Node "MS Specials NLAlwaysOpened" "GMS_mailer.guide/MailerSettings/Specials/NLAlwaysOpened"
@Next "MS Specials OldTruncate"
@Prev "MS Specials MaxErrorSize"
@Toc  "MS Specials"

Name:      NLAlwaysOpened=<boolean>

   You  can  choose if open the nodelist only at GMS mailer startup or open
and close it when there is a session.


Example:   NLAlwaysOpened=OFF

@EndNode

@Node "MS Specials OldTruncate" "GMS_mailer.guide/MailerSettings/Specials/OldTruncate"
@Next "MS Specials OutFReqs"
@Prev "MS Specials NLAlwaysOpened"
@Toc  "MS Specials"

Name:      OldTruncate=<boolean>

   When  this  keyword  is  enabled,  GMS mailer uses the old style code to
truncate a file.

   For a bug of the DCFFS you must set ON with it.


Example:   OldTruncate=OFF

@EndNode

@Node "MS Specials OutFReqs" "GMS_mailer.guide/MailerSettings/Specials/OutFReqs"
@Next "MS Specials Pickup"
@Prev "MS Specials OldTruncate"
@Toc  "MS Specials"

Name:      OutFReqs=<boolean>

   Indicates that the system will accept and process file requests received
during outbound calls.  In other words, the calling system will do a second
turnaround  for  uni-directional protocols, to send the files requested, at
his cost.


Example:   OutFReqs=OFF

@EndNode

@Node "MS Specials Pickup" "GMS_mailer.guide/MailerSettings/Specials/Pickup"
@Next "MS Specials PresentAkas"
@Prev "MS Specials OutFReqs"
@Toc  "MS Specials"

Name:      Pickup=<All|Primary|None>

   Select what mail and files to pickup (receive) from the remote system.

 - All:     For all addresses.
 - Primary: For primary address only.
 - None:    Do not pick up mail or files at all.


   To  deliver mail to a system but no pick up any existing mail, you could
do the following:

   Run GMS_mailer line x Pickup=None CallNode=2:254/524@fidonet.org


Example:   Pickup=All

@EndNode

@Node "MS Specials PresentAkas" "GMS_mailer.guide/MailerSettings/Specials/PresentAkas"
@Next "MS Specials ProcessOnly4D"
@Prev "MS Specials Pickup"
@Toc  "MS Specials"

Name:      PresentAkas=<All|Shown|Main>

   In incoming calls select which akas present to the remote side.

 - All:     present all the akas
 - Shown:   present only the akas matching to the shown
 - Main:    present only the main akas matching to the shown-mainaka


   This option is included to allow the handshake with systems that have many
akas (>30) with software that can handle a limited number of aka.


Example:   PresentAkas=All

@EndNode

@Node "MS Specials ProcessOnly4D" "GMS_mailer.guide/MailerSettings/Specials/ProcessOnly4D"
@Next "MS Specials RetryDosRead"
@Prev "MS Specials PresentAkas"
@Toc  "MS Specials"

Name:      ProcessOnly4D=<boolean>

   Send to the remote system only the files with 4D name.

For example: 2.331.106.0.OUT
             2.331.106.0.FLO


Example:   ProcessOnly4D=ON

@EndNode

@Node "MS Specials RetryDosRead" "GMS_mailer.guide/MailerSettings/Specials/RetryDosRead"
@Next "MS Specials RetryDosWrite"
@Prev "MS Specials ProcessOnly4D"
@Toc  "MS Specials"

Name:      RetryDosRead=<decimal>

   When there is a read error, retry <x> times.


Example:   RetryDosRead=5

@EndNode

@Node "MS Specials RetryDosWrite" "GMS_mailer.guide/MailerSettings/Specials/RetryDosWrite"
@Next "MS Specials SkipDupes"
@Prev "MS Specials RetryDosRead"
@Toc  "MS Specials"

Name:      RetryDosWrite=<boolean>

   When there is a write error, retry <x> times.


Example:   RetryDosWrite=5

@EndNode

@Node "MS Specials SkipDupes" "GMS_mailer.guide/MailerSettings/Specials/SkipDupes"
@Next "MS Specials SlotsType"
@Prev "MS Specials RetryDosWrite"
@Toc  "MS Specials"

Name:      SkipDupes=<boolean>

   When  this  keyword  is  enabled  you tell GMS mailer to skip to receive
files that you have in your inbound directory.


Example:   SkipDupes=OFF

@EndNode

@Node "MS Specials SlotsType" "GMS_mailer.guide/MailerSettings/Specials/SlotsType"
@Next "MS Specials TaskPri"
@Prev "MS Specials SkipDupes"
@Toc  "MS Specials"

Name:      SlotsType=<Normal|File|CarrierLost>

   This deteminates what GMS has to do when a ProtectedSlots time starts.


   Normal:      It doesn't abort.
   File:        Abort when the current sending/receiving files are sent/received.
   CarrierLost: Abort the connection immediately.


Example:   SlotsType=Normal

@EndNode

@Node "MS Specials TaskPri" "GMS_mailer.guide/MailerSettings/Specials/TaskPri"
@Next "MS Specials TrapListPatch"
@Prev "MS Specials SlotsType"
@Toc  "MS Specials"

Name:      TaskPri=<value>

   Set the priority of the mailer task.


Example:   TaskPri=0

@EndNode

@Node "MS Specials TrapListPatch" "GMS_mailer.guide/MailerSettings/Specials/TrapListPatch"
@Prev "MS Specials TaskPri"
@Toc  "MS Specials"

Name:      TrapListPatch=<boolean>

   Fixes a bugged function of the traplist.library to prevent a guru.


Example:   TrapListPatch=ON

@EndNode

@Node "MS System" "GMS_mailer.guide/MailerSettings/System"
@Next "MS Voice"
@Prev "MS Specials"
@Toc  "CFG MailerSettings"

   @{b}System options@{ub}


   Your system set up...

 @{" Accounting        " Link "MS System Accounting"}
 @{" AcctMax           " Link "MS System AcctMax"}
 @{" Boss              " Link "MS System Boss"}
 @{" CallNode          " Link "MS System CallNode"}
 @{" CallNumber        " Link "MS System CallNumber"}
 @{" DialTimeout       " Link "MS System DialTimeout"}
 @{" Flags             " Link "MS System Flags"}
 @{" InactivityTimeout " Link "MS System InactivityTimeout"}
 @{" Name              " Link "MS System Name"}
 @{" Nodelist          " Link "MS System Nodelist"}
 @{" Password          " Link "MS System Password"}
 @{" Phone             " Link "MS System Phone"}
 @{" Place             " Link "MS System Place"}
 @{" RedialDelay       " Link "MS System RedialDelay"}
 @{" ResetTimeout      " Link "MS System ResetTimeout"}
 @{" Retries           " Link "MS System Retries"}
 @{" Ringings          " Link "MS System Ringings"}
 @{" Rings             " Link "MS System Rings"}
 @{" RingTimeout       " Link "MS System RingTimeout"}
 @{" SysOp             " Link "MS System SysOp"}
 @{" UnitCost          " Link "MS System UnitCost"}
 @{" UnitLength        " Link "MS System UnitLength"}

@EndNode

@Node "MS System Accounting" "GMS_mailer.guide/MailerSettings/System/Accounting"
@Next "MS System AcctMax"
@Toc  "MS System"

Name:      Accounting=<boolean>

   If enabled, GMS mailer will keep a database of:

     - The number of calls made to a node
     - The number of calls received from that node
     - The number of successful sessions
     - The number of failed sessions
     - The number of BUSY results
     - The number of NO CARRIER, NO ANSWER results
     - The number of VOICE results
     - The TrxID value of the last successful session
     - The cost of a call.


Example:   Accounting=OFF

@EndNode

@Node "MS System AcctMax" "GMS_mailer.guide/MailerSettings/System/AcctMax"
@Next "MS System Boss"
@Prev "MS System Accounting"
@Toc  "MS System"

Name:      AcctMax=<limits>

   When  accounting  is  enabled,  GMS  mailer,  when  instructed to call a
certain  node,  will  check whether or not this node exceeds the accounting
limits set by this keyword.

   The limits parameter, a single string enclosed in quotes, sets:

     - The number of calls out
     - The number of failed sessions
     - The number of BUSY results
     - The number of NO CARRIER, NO ANSWER and NO DIALTONE results
     - The number of VOICE results
     - The maximum cost of a call


Examples:  AcctMax="50 10 -1 -1 0 2500"
           AcctMax="-1 -1 -1 -1 -1 -1"

@EndNode

@Node "MS System Boss" "GMS_mailer.guide/MailerSettings/System/Boss"
@Next "MS System CallNode"
@Prev "MS System AcctMax"
@Toc  "MS System"

Name:      Boss=<address>

   Specifies    the    FidoNet    address    of    your    boss,    as   in
`2:331/213@fidonet.org'.   Please  be  careful as not to leave out the zone
and  point  information  when your boss node is capable of four dimensional
addressing.


Example:   Boss=2:331/213@fidonet.org

@EndNode

@Node "MS System CallNode" "GMS_mailer.guide/MailerSettings/System/CallNode"
@Next "MS System CallNumber"
@Prev "MS System Boss"
@Toc  "MS System"

Name:      CallNode=<multiaddr>

   With this keyword, GMS mailer call a single node or many in a row.

   For use this keyword, the nodelist is needed.


Examples:  CallNode=2:331/205@fidonet.org
           CallNode="2:334/21@fidonet.org 2:334/22@fidonet.org"

@EndNode

@Node "MS System CallNumber" "GMS_mailer.guide/MailerSettings/System/CallNumber"
@Next "MS System DialTimeout"
@Prev "MS System CallNode"
@Toc  "MS System"

Name:      CallNumber=<phone-number>

   With this keyword, GMS mailer call a node with the phone number.


Example:   CallNumber=0372-36302

@EndNode

@Node "MS System DialTimeout" "GMS_mailer.guide/MailerSettings/System/DialTimeout"
@Next "MS System Flags"
@Prev "MS System CallNumber"
@Toc  "MS System"

Name:      DialTimeout=<seconds>

   Specifies the time in seconds how long GMS mailer will wait for a
CONNECT, BUSY, NO CARRIER, VOICE or ERROR response from the modem after
sending a dial command. If the given timeout expires, GMS mailer will give
up waiting and re-initialize the modem.


Example:   DialTimeout=30

@EndNode

@Node "MS System Flags" "GMS_mailer.guide/MailerSettings/System/Flags"
@Next "MS System InactivityTimeout"
@Prev "MS System DialTimeout"
@Toc  "MS System"

Name:      Flags=<string>

   Are  the  modem  flags that will be send in the EMSI handshake.  Is this
keyword is not set, GMS mailer will look in the nodelist.


Example:   Flags="CM,XX,H16,V32T,VFC,V34"

@EndNode

@Node "MS System InactivityTimeout" "GMS_mailer.guide/MailerSettings/System/InactivityTimeout"
@Next "MS System Name"
@Prev "MS System Flags"
@Toc  "MS System"

Name:      InactivityTimeout=<decimal>

   If in an incoming call the remote system does not respond at the handshake
and there is not set the BBS, GMS mailer will hang up.


Example:   InactivityTimeout=30

@EndNode

@Node "MS System Name" "GMS_mailer.guide/MailerSettings/System/Name"
@Next "MS System Nodelist"
@Prev "MS System InactivityTimeout"
@Toc  "MS System"

Name:      Name=<string>

   Is the name of this system. It will be sent to the remote system during the
session handshake.


Example:   Name="Denei Shoojo Ai -<GMS & EMS Development>- USRobotics V.everything"

@EndNode

@Node "MS System Nodelist" "GMS_mailer.guide/MailerSettings/System/Nodelist"
@Next "MS System Password"
@Prev "MS System Name"
@Toc  "MS System"

Name:      Nodelist=<string>

   Is the directory that contain the nodelist. At this time, GMS only supports
the traplist.library.


Example:   Nodelist="Mail:Nodelist/"


See also:     @{"CallNode" Link "MS System CallNode"}

@EndNode

@Node "MS System Password" "GMS_mailer.guide/MailerSettings/System/Password"
@Next "MS System Phone"
@Prev "MS System Nodelist"
@Toc  "MS System"

Name:      Password=<passwd>

   Specifies the password that will be send to the remote system.


Example:   Password=PASSWD

@EndNode

@Node "MS System Phone" "GMS_mailer.guide/MailerSettings/System/Phone"
@Next "MS System Place"
@Prev "MS System Password"
@Toc  "MS System"

Name:      Phone=<phone number>

   Is the phone number that will be send in the EMSI handshake.


Example:   Phone=+39-372-36302

@EndNode

@Node "MS System Place" "GMS_mailer.guide/MailerSettings/System/Place"
@Next "MS System RedialDelay"
@Prev "MS System Phone"
@Toc  "MS System"

Name:      Place=<string>

   Is the place of the system that will be send during the EMSI handshake.


Example:   Place=Italy

@EndNode

@Node "MS System RedialDelay" "GMS_mailer.guide/MailerSettings/System/RedialDelay"
@Next "MS System ResetTimeout"
@Prev "MS System Place"
@Toc  "MS System"

Name:      RedialDelay=<seconds>

   This specifies the amount of time GMS mailer spends idling between calls
to a system.


Example:   RedialDelay=60

@EndNode

@Node "MS System ResetTimeout" "GMS_mailer.guide/MailerSettings/System/ResetTimeout"
@Next "MS System Retries"
@Prev "MS System RedialDelay"
@Toc  "MS System"

Name:      ResetTimeout=<minutes>

   Using this switch, you can set the time in minutes between automatic
modem resets. Sometimes needed or else the modem will hang.


Example:   ResetTimeout=15

@EndNode

@Node "MS System Retries" "GMS_mailer.guide/MailerSettings/System/Retries"
@Next "MS System Ringings"
@Prev "MS System ResetTimeout"
@Toc  "MS System"

Name:      Retries=<retries>

   When calling a system, this instructs GMS mailer not to exit on a failed
call (eg. line is busy), but to try it thus often again. Between the calls,
GMS mailer will spend <RedialDelay> seconds waiting.


Example:   Retries=50

@EndNode

@Node "MS System Ringings" "GMS_mailer.guide/MailerSettings/System/Ringings"
@Next "MS System Rings"
@Prev "MS System Retries"
@Toc  "MS System"

Name:      Ringings=<number>

   This is the number of times GMS mailer  will allow another system to keep
the phone "ringing" on an outgoing call.


Example:   Ringings=10

@EndNode

@Node "MS System Rings" "GMS_mailer.guide/MailerSettings/System/Rings"
@Next "MS System RingTimeout"
@Prev "MS System Ringings"
@Toc  "MS System"

Name:      Rings=<number>

   Number of rings to wait before answering an incoming call.


Example:   Rings=2

@EndNode

@Node "MS System RingTimeout" "GMS_mailer.guide/MailerSettings/System/RingTimeout"
@Next "MS System SysOp"
@Prev "MS System Rings"
@Toc  "MS System"

Name:      RingTimeout=<seconds>

   Is the number of seconds that GMS mailer attends for RING message.


Example:   RingTimeout=5

@EndNode

@Node "MS System SysOp" "GMS_mailer.guide/MailerSettings/System/SysOp"
@Next "MS System UnitCost"
@Prev "MS System RingTimeout"
@Toc  "MS System"

Name:      SysOp=<name>

   Specifies the SysOp name. This string will be sent to the remote system
during the session handshake.


Example:   SysOp="Mirko Viviani"

@EndNode

@Node "MS System UnitCost" "GMS_mailer.guide/MailerSettings/System/UnitCost"
@Next "MS System UnitLength"
@Prev "MS System SysOp"
@Toc  "MS System"

Name:      UnitCost=<decimal>

   Specifies the cost of an unit.


Example:   UnitCost=150

@EndNode

@Node "MS System UnitLength" "GMS_mailer.guide/MailerSettings/System/UnitLength"
@Prev "MS System UnitCost"
@Toc  "MS System"

Name:      UnitLength=<seconds>

   Specifies the length of an unit.


Example:   UnitLength=40

@EndNode

@Node "MS Voice" "GMS_mailer.guide/MailerSettings/Voice"
@Prev "MS System"
@Toc  "CFG MailerSettings"

   @{b}Voice options@{ub}


   With these keywords you can configure a complete Voice session.

 @{" VoiceInCommand  " Link "MS Voice VoiceInCommand"}
 @{" VoiceInPri      " Link "MS Voice VoiceInPri"}
 @{" VoiceInStack    " Link "MS Voice VoiceInStack"}
 @{" VoiceOutCommand " Link "MS Voice VoiceOutCommand"}
 @{" VoiceOutPri     " Link "MS Voice VoiceOutPri"}
 @{" VoiceOutStack   " Link "MS Voice VoiceOutStack"}
 @{" VoiceString     " Link "MS Voice VoiceString"}

@EndNode

@Node "MS Voice VoiceInCommand" "GMS_mailer.guide/MailerSettings/Voice/VoiceInCommand"
@Next "MS Voice VoiceInPri"
@Toc  "MS Voice"

Name:      VoiceInCommand=<command>

   In  Answer  mode ON, when GMS mailer detects a voice connection, it will
spawn this external program.

   There may be embedded %-commands:

   %a      aka of the remote system (one aka per %a)
   %A      all akas of the remote system (space separated)
   %b      baudrate (between computer and modem)
   %B      baudrate (of the actual connection)
   %C      full CONNECT message from the modem
   %s      serial device name
   %u      serial device unit number
   %f      serial device flags
   %r      unique random number (timestamp)
   %l      name of logfile
   %L      name of log callerID
   %Z      zone number of the other system     
   %N      net number of the other system
   %F      fido node number of the other system
   %P      point number of the other system
   %D      domain name of the other system (if available)
   %n      complete address of the other system
   %I      name of <GlobalInbound>
   %O      name of <GlobalOutbound>
   %S      name of Sysop of other system
   %d      direction: 1 if inbound call, -1 if outbound call
   %x      this TrxID string
   %X      remote TrxID string
   %m      line number of this system


Example:   VoiceInCommand="Voice %C"


See also:     @{"VoiceString" Link "MS Voice VoiceString"}

@EndNode

@Node "MS Voice VoiceInPri" "GMS_mailer.guide/MailerSettings/Voice/VoiceInPri"
@Next "MS Voice VoiceInStack"
@Prev "MS Voice VoiceInCommand"
@Toc  "MS Voice"

Name:      VoiceInPri=<pri>

   Set the priority of the <VoiceInCommand> command.


Example:   VoiceInPri=1

@EndNode

@Node "MS Voice VoiceInStack" "GMS_mailer.guide/MailerSettings/Voice/VoiceInStack"
@Next "MS Voice VoiceOutCommand"
@Prev "MS Voice VoiceInCommand"
@Toc  "MS Voice"

Name:      VoiceInStack=<dimensione>

   Set the stack size for <VoiceInCommand> command.


Example:   VoiceInStack=8000

@EndNode

@Node "MS Voice VoiceOutCommand" "GMS_mailer.guide/MailerSettings/Voice/VoiceOutCommand"
@Next "MS Voice VoiceOutPri"
@Prev "MS Voice VoiceInStack"
@Toc  "MS Voice"

Name:      VoiceOutCommand=<command>

   During a call, when GMS mailer detects a voice connection, it will spawn
this external program.

   There may be embedded %-commands:

   %a      aka of the remote system (one aka per %a)
   %A      all akas of the remote system (space separated)
   %b      baudrate (between computer and modem)
   %B      baudrate (of the actual connection)
   %C      full CONNECT message from the modem
   %s      serial device name
   %u      serial device unit number
   %f      serial device flags
   %r      unique random number (timestamp)
   %l      name of logfile
   %L      name of log callerID
   %Z      zone number of the other system     
   %N      net number of the other system
   %F      fido node number of the other system
   %P      point number of the other system
   %D      domain name of the other system (if available)
   %n      complete address of the other system
   %I      name of <GlobalInbound>
   %O      name of <GlobalOutbound>
   %S      name of Sysop of other system
   %d      direction: 1 if inbound call, -1 if outbound call
   %x      this TrxID string
   %X      remote TrxID string
   %m      line number of this system


Example:   VoiceOutCommand="Voice %C"


See also:     @{"VoiceString" Link "MS Voice VoiceString"}

@EndNode

@Node "MS Voice VoiceOutPri" "GMS_mailer.guide/MailerSettings/Voice/VoiceOutPri"
@Next "MS Voice VoiceOutStack"
@Prev "MS Voice VoiceOutCommand"
@Toc  "MS Voice"

Name:      VoiceOutPri=<pri>

   Set the priority of the <VoiceOutCommand> command.


Example:   VoiceOutPri=0

@EndNode

@Node "MS Voice VoiceOutStack" "GMS_mailer.guide/MailerSettings/Voice/VoiceOutStack"
@Next "MS Voice VoiceString"
@Prev "MS Voice VoiceOutCommand"
@Toc  "MS Voice"

Name:      VoiceOutStack=<dimension>

   Set the stack size for <VoiceOutCommand> command.


Example:   VoiceOutStack=8000

@EndNode

@Node "MS Voice VoiceString" "GMS_mailer.guide/MailerSettings/Voice/VoiceString"
@Prev "MS Voice VoiceOutStack"
@Toc  "MS Voice"

Name:      VoiceString=<string>

   Is  the  string  that  GMS  mailer  will search in the CONNECT string to
determine if it is a Voice connection.


Example:   VoiceString=Voice


See also:     @{"VoiceInCommand" Link "MS Voice VoiceInCommand"}, @{"VoiceOutCommand" Link "MS Voice VoiceOutCommand"}

@EndNode

@Node "CFG MailerEditor" "GMS_mailer.guide/The configuration/MailerEditor"
@Next "CFG Externals"
@Prev "CFG MailerSettings"
@Toc "Configuration"

   @{b}MailerEditor@{ub}


   The file is `GMS:Config/Mailer[.x]/MailerEditor'.

 @{" Background         " Link "ME Background"}
 @{" ClearStatus        " Link "ME ClearStatus"}
 @{" ClearTransfers     " Link "ME ClearTransfers"}
 @{" DisplayStatus      " Link "ME DisplayStatus"}
 @{" DisplayTransfers   " Link "ME DisplayTransfers"}
 @{" IconifyAtBBS       " Link "ME IconifyAtBBS"}
 @{" IconifyAtEnd       " Link "ME IconifyAtEnd"}
 @{" MaxLogListLines    " Link "ME MaxLogListLines"}
 @{" RegisterWdMain     " Link "ME RegisterWdMain"}
 @{" TaskPri            " Link "ME TaskPri"}
 @{" TitleBarInfo       " Link "ME TitleBarInfo"}
 @{" UniconifyAtConnect " Link "ME UniconifyAtConnect"}
 @{" WaitForExit        " Link "ME WaitForExit"}
 @{" WindowSize         " Link "ME WindowSize"}

@EndNode

@Node "ME Background" "GMS_mailer.guide/MailerEditor/Background"
@Next "ME ClearStatus"
@Toc  "CFG MailerEditor"

Name:      Background=<boolean>

   Open the main window without activate it. Ensure MUI prefs is also set to
background for the GMS mailer line.


Example:   Background=OFF

@EndNode

@Node "ME ClearStatus" "GMS_mailer.guide/MailerEditor/ClearStatus"
@Next "ME ClearTransfers"
@Prev "ME Background"
@Toc  "CFG MailerEditor"

Name:      ClearStatus=<boolean>

   Clear the Status window at the end of a connection.


Example:   ClearStatus=OFF

@EndNode

@Node "ME ClearTransfers" "GMS_mailer.guide/MailerEditor/ClearTransfers"
@Next "ME DisplayStatus"
@Prev "ME ClearStatus"
@Toc  "CFG MailerEditor"

Name:      ClearTransfers=<boolean>

   Clear Send & Receive windows at the end of a connection.


Example:   ClearTransfers=OFF

@EndNode

@Node "ME DisplayStatus" "GMS_mailer.guide/MailerEditor/DisplayStatus"
@Next "ME DisplayTransfers"
@Prev "ME ClearTransfers"
@Toc  "CFG MailerEditor"

Name:      DisplayStatus=<boolean>

   Show/Hide the Status window.


Example:   DisplayStatus=ON

@EndNode

@Node "ME DisplayTransfers" "GMS_mailer.guide/MailerEditor/DisplayTransfers"
@Next "ME IconifyAtBBS"
@Prev "ME DisplayStatus"
@Toc  "CFG MailerEditor"

Name:      DisplayTransfers=<boolean>

   Show/Hide Send & Receive windows.


Example:   DisplayTransfers=ON

@EndNode

@Node "ME IconifyAtBBS" "GMS_mailer.guide/MailerEditor/IconifyAtBBS"
@Next "ME IconifyAtEnd"
@Prev "ME DisplayTransfers"
@Toc  "CFG MailerEditor"

Name:      IconifyAtBBS=<boolean>

   In Answer=ON, GMS iconifies the GUI at the beginning of a bbs session.


Example:   IconifyAtBBS=OFF

@EndNode

@Node "ME IconifyAtEnd" "GMS_mailer.guide/MailerEditor/IconifyAtEnd"
@Next "ME MaxLogListLines"
@Prev "ME IconifyAtBBS"
@Toc  "CFG MailerEditor"

Name:      IconifyAtEnd=<boolean>

   In Answer=ON, GMS iconifies the GUI at the end of a session.


Example:   IconifyAtEnd=OFF

@EndNode

@Node "ME MaxLogListLines" "GMS_mailer.guide/MailerEditor/MaxLogListLines"
@Next "ME RegisterWdMain"
@Prev "ME IconifyAtEnd"
@Toc  "CFG MailerEditor"

Name:      MaxLogListLines=<decimal>

   Set the max number of lines that you can see in the listview.


Example:   MaxLogListLines=50

@EndNode

@Node "ME RegisterWdMain" "GMS_mailer.guide/MailerEditor/RegisterWdMain"
@Next "ME TaskPri"
@Prev "ME MaxLogListLines"
@Toc  "CFG MailerEditor"

Name:      RegisterWdMain=<One|Two_StatusLog|Two_StatusTrs|Two_LogTrs|Three>

   This keyword change the layout of the editor window.


Example:   RegisterWdMain=One

@EndNode

@Node "ME TaskPri" "GMS_mailer.guide/MailerEditor/TaskPri"
@Next "ME TitleBarInfo"
@Prev "ME RegisterWdMain"
@Toc  "CFG MailerEditor"

Name:      TaskPri=<value>

   Sets the priority of the task.


Example:   TaskPri=1

@EndNode

@Node "ME TitleBarInfo" "GMS_mailer.guide/MailerEditor/TitleBarInfo"
@Next "ME UniconifyAtConnect"
@Prev "ME TaskPri"
@Toc  "CFG MailerEditor"

Name:      TitleBarInfo=<string>

   Set the title of the window.

   o %m   will set the line number of the mailer


Example:   TitleBarInfo="Line %m: 39:101/303@amiganet.ftn"

@EndNode

@Node "ME UniconifyAtConnect" "GMS_mailer.guide/MailerEditor/UniconifyAtConnect"
@Next "ME WaitForExit"
@Prev "ME TitleBarInfo"
@Toc  "CFG MailerEditor"

Name:      UniconifyAtConnect=<boolean>

   In Answer=ON, GMS uniconifies the GUI at the connect.


Example:   UniconifyAtConnect=ON

@EndNode

@Node "ME WaitForExit" "GMS_mailer.guide/MailerEditor/WaitForExit"
@Next "ME WindowSize"
@Prev "ME UniconifyAtConnect"
@Toc  "CFG MailerEditor"

Name:      WaitForExit=<seconds>

   At the end of session, GMS waits <seconds> secs...


Example:   WaitForExit=2


@EndNode

@Node "ME WindowSize" "GMS_mailer.guide/MailerEditor/WindowSize"
@Prev "ME WaitForExit"
@Toc  "CFG MailerEditor"

Name:      WindowSize=<Left/Top/Width/Height>

   Sets the dimension of the mailer window.


Example:   WindowSize=0/0/-1/-1

@EndNode

@Node "CFG Externals" "GMS_mailer.guide/The configuration/Externals"
@Next "CFG ProtectedSlots"
@Prev "CFG MailerEditor"
@Toc "Configuration"

   @{b}Externals@{ub}


   The file is `GMS:Config/Mailer[.x]/Externals'.

 @{" Title " Link "EXT Title"}
    @{" Command  " Link "EXT Command"}
    @{" Stack    " Link "EXT Stack"}
    @{" ShortCut " Link "EXT ShortCut"}
    @{" HotKey   " Link "EXT HotKey"}

    @{" SubTitle " Link "EXT SubTitle"}
       @{" Command  " Link "EXT Sub Command"}
       @{" Stack    " Link "EXT Sub Stack"}
       @{" ShortCut " Link "EXT Sub ShortCut"}
       @{" HotKey   " Link "EXT Sub HotKey"}


Example:

   Title="Call"
      SubTitle="Amiga & Technology"
         Command="rx rexx:GMS_CallNode %m -1 -1 39:101/400@amiganet.ftn 39:101/404@amiganet.ftn 39:101/408@amiganet.ftn"

      SubTitle="Maui"
         Command="rx rexx:GMS_CallNode %m -1 -1 39:102/1@amiganet.ftn 39:102/2@amiganet.ftn"
         ShortCut=M

      SubTitle=""

      SubTitle="LOGiC PALACE"
         Command="rx rexx:GMS_CallNode %m -1 -1 39:110/301@amiganet.ftn 39:110/302@amiganet.ftn"

      SubTitle="amistep.osn.de"
         Command="rx rexx:GMS_CallNode %m -1 -1 39:171/101@amiganet.ftn"

   Title="Import..."
      Command="rx EMS:Rexx/Import.ems"
      Stack 30000

   Title="Export..."
      Command="rx EMS:Rexx/Export.ems"
      Stack 30000

@EndNode

@Node "EXT Title" "GMS_mailer.guide/Externals/Title"
@Toc  "CFG Externals"

Name:      Title=<string>

   Set the title of the menuitem.

   If you set to "" you will see a Bar label.


Example:   Title=""

@EndNode

@Node "EXT Command" "GMS_mailer.guide/Externals/Command"
@Next "EXT Stack"
@Toc  "EXT Title"

Name:      Command=<string>

   Set the command associated to the menuitem.

   o %m   will set the line number of the mailer


Example:   Command="rx EMS:Rexx/Import.ems"

@EndNode

@Node "EXT Stack" "GMS_mailer.guide/Externals/Stack"
@Next "EXT ShortCut"
@Prev "EXT Command"
@Toc  "EXT Title"

Name:      Stack=<decimal>

   Set the stack of the menu item command


Example:   Stack=30000

@EndNode

@Node "EXT ShortCut" "GMS_mailer.guide/Externals/ShortCut"
@Next "EXT HotKey"
@Prev "EXT Stack"
@Toc  "EXT Title"

Name:      ShortCut=<char>

   Set the shortcut that will be display in the menu.


Example:   ShortCut=M

@EndNode

@Node "EXT HotKey" "GMS_mailer.guide/Externals/HotKey"
@Next "EXT SubTitle"
@Prev "EXT ShortCut"
@Toc  "EXT Title"

Name:      HotKey=<string>

   Set an hotkey to run the menu item command.


Example:   HotKey="alt d"

@EndNode

@Node "EXT SubTitle" "GMS_mailer.guide/Externals/SubTitle"
@Prev "EXT HotKey"
@Toc  "EXT Title"

Name:      SubTitle=<string>

   Set the title of a sub-menuitem.

   If you set to "" you will see a Bar label.


Example:   SubTitle=""

@EndNode

@Node "EXT Sub Command" "GMS_mailer.guide/Externals/SubTitle/Command"
@Next "EXT Sub Stack"
@Toc  "EXT SubTitle"

Name:      Command=<string>

   Set the command associated to the sub-menuitem.

   o %m   will set the line number of the mailer


Example:   Command="rx EMS:Rexx/Import.ems"

@EndNode

@Node "EXT Sub Stack" "GMS_mailer.guide/Externals/SubTitle/Stack"
@Next "EXT Sub ShortCut"
@Prev "EXT Sub Command"
@Toc  "EXT SubTitle"

Name:      Stack=<decimal>

   Set the stack of the sub-menu item command.


Example:   Stack=30000

@EndNode

@Node "EXT Sub ShortCut" "GMS_mailer.guide/Externals/SubTitle/ShortCut"
@Next "EXT Sub HotKey"
@Prev "EXT Sub Stack"
@Toc  "EXT SubTitle"

Name:      ShortCut=<char>

   Set the shortcut that will be display in the sub-menu.


Example:   ShortCut=M

@EndNode

@Node "EXT Sub HotKey" "GMS_mailer.guide/Externals/SubTitle/HotKey"
@Prev "EXT Sub ShortCut"
@Toc  "EXT SubTitle"

Name:      HotKey=<string>

   Set an hotkey to run the sub-menu item command.


Example:   HotKey="alt d"

@EndNode

@Node "CFG ProtectedSlots" "GMS_mailer.guide/The configuration/ProtectedSlots"
@Prev "CFG Externals"
@Toc "Configuration"

   @{b}ProtectedSlots@{ub}


   The file is `GMS:Config/Mailer[.x]/ProtectedSlots'.

 @{" Node " Link "PRO Node"}
    @{" Start    " Link "PRO Start"}
    @{" End      " Link "PRO End"}
    @{" Protocol " Link "PRO Protocol"}


Example:

   Node=2:331/205@fidonet.org
      Start=1:00:00
      End=1:10:00

   Node=39:101/300@amiganet.ftn
      Start=7:30:00
      End=7:40:00
      Protocol=DirectZap


   This simple example set the rule for to nodes:

Between  <1:00:00>  and  <1:10:00>  GMS accepts sessions only from the node
<2:331/205@fidonet.org>

Between  <7:30:00>  and  <7:40:00>  GMS accepts sessions only from the node
<39:101/300@amiganet.ftn>  with the DirectZap protocol.  If the caller does
not offer DirectZap protocol the session aborts.

@EndNode

@Node "PRO Node" "GMS_mailer.guide/The configuration/ProtectedSlots/Node"
@Toc "CFG ProtectedSlots"

Name:      Node=<node>

   Between <Start> and <End> time GMS accepts calls only from this node.


Example:   Node=2:331/213@fidonet.org

@EndNode

@Node "PRO Start" "GMS_mailer.guide/The configuration/ProtectedSlots/Node/Start"
@Next "PRO End"
@Toc "PRO Node"

Name:      Start=<hours:min:secs>

   Set the time when the node can call.


Example:   Start=6:00:00

@EndNode

@Node "PRO End" "GMS_mailer.guide/The configuration/ProtectedSlots/Node/End"
@Next "PRO Protocol"
@Prev "PRO Start"
@Toc "PRO Node"

Name:      End=<hours:min:secs>

   Set the time that set the finish of the priority for the node.


Example:   End=6:10:00

@EndNode

@Node "PRO Protocol" "GMS_mailer.guide/The configuration/ProtectedSlots/Node/Protocol"
@Prev "PRO End"
@Toc "PRO Node"

Name:      Protocol=<Xmodem|ZedZip|ZedZap|DirectZap|Hydra>

   With  this  keyword  GMS  accept a session from the node <Node> with the
protocol <Protocol>.  Else it drop the carrier.


Example:   Protocol=DirectZap

@EndNode

@Node "GUI" "GMS_mailer.guide/GUI"
@Next "ARexx Interface"
@Prev "Configuration"
@Toc  "Main"

   @{b}Graphical User Interface of GMS mailer@{ub}


   GMS  mailer  Graphical  User  Interface utilises the features of MUI.
With MUI you can configure almost everything of the GMS mailer GUI, besides
you  can  control  everything with the mouse or even with the keyboard.  In
order  to  completelly  exploit  such  a powerful interface you SHOULD read
@{"MUI's documentation" link "MUI"} carefully.

   The main window of the GMS mailer User-Interface (GUI) consist of mainly
4 SubWindow:


  @{" Status Window  " link "GUI Status Window"}   Window which shows the Status
  @{" Log Window     " link "GUI Log Window"}   Window which shows the Log
  @{" Send Window    " link "GUI Send Window"}   Window which shows the Send transfer
  @{" Receive Window " link "GUI Receive Window"}   Window which shows the Receive transfer

  @{" Menus          " link "GUI Menus"}   Menus of the main window
  @{" HotKeys        " link "GUI HotKeys"}   Standard hotkeys...
@EndNode

@Node "GUI Status Window" "GMS_mailer.guide/GUI/Status Window"
@Next "GUI Log Window"
@Toc  "GUI"

   @{b}Status Window@{ub}


Here GMS mailer shows some information about the current session:


  Status           - Is the status of the session...
  Connection at    - Is the CONNECT string...
  Redial           - Is the count-down timer for the redial delay...

  Handshake        - Is the handshake used in the session...
  Protocol         - Is the protocol used in the session...
  Using            - Is the name of the remote mailer...

  Node             - Is the main node of the remote system...
  SysOp            - Is the sysop name of the remote system...
  Phone Number     - Is the phone number of the remote system...
  BBS Name         - Is the name of the remote system...

  Session CPS Rate - Is the total cps rate of the current session...
  Total errors     - Are the total errors of the current session...

@EndNode

@Node "GUI Log Window" "GMS_mailer.guide/GUI/Log Window"
@Next "GUI Send Window"
@Prev "GUI Status Window"
@Toc  "GUI"

   @{b}Log Window@{ub}


Here GMS mailer shows the log in action.

Of  course  you  can  use  all  the configured keyboard shortcuts for a MUI
listview.
@EndNode

@Node "GUI Send Window" "GMS_mailer.guide/GUI/Send Window"
@Next "GUI Receive Window"
@Prev "GUI Log Window"
@Toc  "GUI"

   @{b}Send Window@{ub}


Here GMS mailer shows some information about the sending of a file:


  Name         - Is the name of the current file to send...
  Len          - Is the length of the file / length transferred...
  Blk size/Bad - Is the size of the block / number of bad pkts...
  Time         - Is the total time / remaining time...

@EndNode

@Node "GUI Receive Window" "GMS_mailer.guide/GUI/Receive Window"
@Prev "GUI Send Window"
@Toc  "GUI"

   @{b}Receive Window@{ub}


Here GMS mailer shows some information about the receiving of a file:


  Name         - Is the name of the current file to receive...
  Len          - Is the length of the file / length transferred...
  Blk size/Bad - Is the size of the block / number of bad pkts...
  Time         - Is the total time / remaining time...

@EndNode

@Node "GUI Menus" "GMS_mailer.guide/GUI/Menus"
@Next "GUI HotKeys"
@Prev "GUI Receive Window"
@Toc  "GUI"

   @{b}Menus@{ub}


  @{" Project   " link "GUI Menus _Project"}
    About
    Iconify
    Hide
    Quit

  @{" Misc      " link "GUI Menus _Misc"}
    Answer...
    Reset...
    Hang up...
    Reload cfgs...

  @{" Externals " link "GUI Menus _Externals"}
    What do you want...

@EndNode

