@Node "ARexx Commands" "GMS_mailer.guide/ARexx commands"
@Next "Gli script"
@Prev "GUI"
@Toc "Main"

   @{b}ARexx commands@{ub}


   All ARexx commands are included in GMS_mailer_rexx.library, which should
be  opened  at  the  beginning  of  each  GMS  script  with  the  following
instructions:

     signal on error
     signal on syntax
     
     if( ~show( 'l', "GMS_mailer_rexx.library" ) ) then
     do
        if( ~addlib( "GMS_mailer_rexx.library", 0, -30, 0 ) )then
        do
           say "Could not open GMS_mailer_rexx.library"
           exit 10
        end
     end

   GMS  stores  a  few  data for each script that asks for its service, but
unfortunately,  there's  no  way  for GMS to know when a script ends, so it
cannot  automatically  free  the  memory  it  allocated  for  that  script.
Therefore,  you  must do it manually (see @{"GMS_mailer_FreeScriptData" Link "GMS_mailer_FreeScriptData"}), these
instructions at the end of your script:

     call GMS_mailer_FreeScriptData()
     return 0

   Special  care should be taken for the case of a premature and unexpected
script  termination  due  to  an  error;  your  script  should include this
error-trapping routine:

     error:
     syntax:
     
     error_text = GMS_mailer_LastError()
     
     if error_text = '' then error_text = rc ErrorText( rc )
     
     say '| ***BREAK: error at' sigl error_text
     
     call GMS_mailer_FreeScriptData()
     exit rc


 @{" GMS_mailer_FreeScriptData " Link "GMS_mailer_FreeScriptData"} 
 @{" GMS_mailer_LastError      " Link "GMS_mailer_LastError"} 
 @{" GMS_mailer_System_Alloc   " Link "GMS_mailer_System_Alloc"} 
 @{" GMS_mailer_System_Free    " Link "GMS_mailer_System_Free"} 
 @{" GMS_mailer_System_Version " Link "GMS_mailer_System_Version"} 
 @{" GMS_mailer_Call_Node      " Link "GMS_mailer_Call_Node"} 
 @{" GMS_mailer_Call_Number    " Link "GMS_mailer_Call_Number"} 
 @{" GMS_mailer_Config_Modify  " Link "GMS_mailer_Config_Modify"} 
 @{" GMS_mailer_Config_Delete  " Link "GMS_mailer_Config_Delete"} 
 @{" GMS_mailer_Log_Write      " Link "GMS_mailer_Log_Write"} 
 @{" GMS_mailer_Modem_Answer   " Link "GMS_mailer_Modem_Answer"} 
 @{" GMS_mailer_Modem_Reset    " Link "GMS_mailer_Modem_Reset"} 
 @{" GMS_mailer_Session_Abort  " Link "GMS_mailer_Session_Abort"} 
 @{" GMS_mailer_Session_Quit   " Link "GMS_mailer_Session_Quit"} 
 @{" GMS_mailer_Session_Spawn  " Link "GMS_mailer_Session_Spawn"} 
 @{" GMS_mailer_Status         " Link "GMS_mailer_Status"} 
 @{" GMS_mailer_Status_Report  " Link "GMS_mailer_Status_Report"} 


   In the command descriptions a few conventions apply:

   * For  all  commands,  the arguments and (possibly) a result are listed.
     When a command returns a result, you should use this syntax:

          <result> = <command>( <arguments>, ... , <arguments> )

     or, in case you do not care at all about the result,

          CALL <command>( <arguments>, ... , <arguments> )

   * If an argument is enclosed in `[]' brackets, it is optional.

   * If  an  argument is not enclosed by `<>', the only possible values for
     that  argument  are  the different strings that, separated by a (`|'),
     make up its name.

   * If an argument includes the ``var name'' or ``stem'' specification, it
     means  it  is an indirect argument; you should not pass GMS its value,
     but rather the name of a variable or a stem that holds it.


@EndNode

@Node "GMS_mailer_FreeScriptData" "GMS_mailer.guide/ARexx commands/GMS_mailer_FreeScriptData"
@Next "GMS_mailer_LastError"
@Toc "ARexx Commands"

@{b}GMS_mailer_FreeScriptData@{ub}


   Free all memory of current script.


